Pez were originally invented as anti-smoking mints.
In the 1920s, Pez were marketed as an alternative to smoking. Pez is a shortened version of the German word (Pfefferminz), which means peppermint - and the first flavor of the candy was mint.
On British Evacuation Day in 1783, George Washington feasted on this carrot cake.
Brussels sprouts, kale, broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, and kohlrabi all come from the same plant.
Pasta is not Italian. Marco Polo brought it to Venice from China. As a matter of fact, the oldest type of pasta (well… noodle, really) is four thousand years old and used to be made out of millet.

Pasta was a common side dish during the Middle Ages and Renaissance, even in Italy. However, it wasn't until recently that it became a staple of Italian cuisine. Pasta became a popular main dish in Naples in the 17th Century. Coincidentally, around the same time a food crisis had shortened the meat supplies in local markets.

Pizza Margherita was a 19th Century invention and was named after Italy’s queen in 1889. The pizza was supposed to feature Italy’s colours and was prepared for Queen Margherita by a baker named Raffaele Esposito of Da Pietro.
The Spanish were the first to use tomatoes to make sauces. They were then followed by the Italians. Tomato sauce was often used to accompany meat or fish dishes.
A single cargo ship in the 2nd Century, bringing black pepper from India to Europe would pay the annual salary of around 7000 soldiers. That’s how expensive pepper was!
Salt used to be a trading currency back in the day. Salary, in latin, derives from the word salt.

Pepper remained so precious that the king of England appointed the The Pepperers' Guild as custodians of his weights to ensure that pepper was accurately weighed. This happened in 1180. Later, the Pepperers’ Guild merged with the Spicers’ Guild to form the Company of Grossers (where the word 'grocer' derives from).

When tomatoes were brought to Europe (during the Columbian Exchange), their only use was decorative. They used to taste sour and seemed suspicious since they are part of the toxic nightshade family. The fruit’s now defining sweet taste was bred at a later stage, most likely by the Italians.

Chilli peppers come from Mesoamerica. They were transported to Europe during the Columbian Exchange, where they spread further East. Europeans domesticated and engineered them to be more palatable (less spicy) and bigger, and this is how the bell pepper appeared.

Before the 17th Century, spices were scarce, expensive, and only belonged to the ruling classes. With technological advances, they became more accessible and thus more affordable for the masses. At that point the elites started looking for other luxury products, such as butter and pastry.

Ancient Greeks used oyster shells to cast some votes. In trials, the jury would write the verdict onto the shell of an oyster. This points to the origin of the word 'ostracise' ('ostreon' is the ancient Greek word for 'oyster').

In 1516 Bavaria instated 'Reinheitsgebot', a purity law that allowed beer to be made using only water, barley and hops (yeast had not beed discovered and was occurring naturally). This was to avoid replacing hops with other bitter plants – a common practice (some of which poisonous), and barley with wheat (essential for bread). It is also one of the very first food safety laws in history.

During the 19th Century, the English set harsh and restrictive controls over the Irish food supply. They brought the most valuable ingredients back to England, leaving the Irish to eat almost exclusively potatoes. (This happened around the same time as the Great Famine when potato crops got destroyed by blight.)
China is the world’s largest carrot producer. In 2011, it accounted for over 45% of the global carrot output.

During WWII the Brits made the Germans believe that their pilots could see in the dark thanks to a carrot-heavy diet. This made British innovations such as improved radar systems and red light in the cockpit (that protected the pilots’ eyesight at night) harder for the Germans to figure out.
